n indigeneity, food systems, climate action—are broached in challenging ways. The twenty authors whose original work is compiled here demonstrate the scope for continued, critical, comparative conversation across francophone and anglophone divides. The book offers a significant resource for understanding the intersecting field and practice of urban studies in Quebec and in B.C. and for spurring its further evolution. A French version of this book is also available.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn French.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aEDUCATION / Curricula.2bisacsh  aBritish Columbia.  aQuébec.  aurban policy.  aurban studies.  aurban theory.1 aCousin, Vincent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDanis, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJeffrey, Denis, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aJeffrey, Denis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLéger, Diane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaxwell, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPoint, Christophe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrairat, Eirick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobichaud, Ariane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRugira, Jeanne-Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchwimmer, Marina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSenécal, Mathilde, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSt-Pierre, Aurel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSt-Vincent, Lise-Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package: